properties.description: Stamford has remained the "finest stone town in England" due to its prosperity drawn from the wool trade and its historic position as a mail coach interchange on the Great North Road almost halfway between London and York.
properties.name: Stamford
North Cotes
properties.note: Historically called North Coates, more commonly referred to as North Cotes (spelt without an 'a').

properties.name: Burton le Coggles
properties.note: Name appears as Burton Coggles on route signs
properties.source:name: Village signposts

properties.description: Edenham is a village situated on the A151 Road. The East Glen River flows through the village. Notable features include the St Michael and all Angels church and The Five Bells pub.
properties.name: Edenham
Garthorpe
properties.note: location based on surrounding village signs

properties.description: Folkingham's market place gives the appearance of a town, while the surroundings a village, reflecting its history (it was previously a town). It is located on the A15 road, and has a church, and previously had a castle (later converted into a jail).
properties.name: Folkingham

properties.description: Located on the A15 road, Bourne is a historic market town containing castle earthworks. The Abbey Church is the oldest building in the town, while other buildings such as Baldock's Mill, Austerby Manor House and the Red Hall are also historic.
properties.name: Bourne
Elsea Park
properties.note: As Elsea Park building work continues, this will need to move to a more central position

properties.description: Austerby was previously separate from Bourne in previous years, but as Bourne grew, it was absorbed. It previously had its own shops, and is still home to some historically significant buildings, such as Austerby Manor House.
properties.name: Austerby
Eastgate
properties.note: Eastgate was a short distance from Bourne, and when the railways were built, it was further cut off. It maintains some historic buildings, such as The Anchor pub.
